01:33:25.980 --> 01:33:26.980
Oh, I'm loving it.

01:33:26.980 --> 01:33:27.980
Oh, are you?

01:33:27.980 --> 01:33:29.980
Oh, good, because I am too.

01:33:29.980 --> 01:33:34.980
Newport. Would you consider Newport to be part of the levels?

01:33:34.980 --> 01:33:37.980
No, not from Liswery onwards.

01:33:37.980 --> 01:33:45.980
Once the land starts to rise at Liswery towards Summerton, towards Chepster Road, the land rises.

01:33:45.980 --> 01:33:49.980
No. Up as far as Summerton.

01:33:49.980 --> 01:33:55.980
And you can imagine it's got its name from the fact that it was the summer grazing grounds.

01:33:55.980 --> 01:33:59.980
It doesn't look like spelling the same.

01:33:59.980 --> 01:34:11.980
But David will tell you his father remembers that farmed right up as far as what we call Corporation Road where the bridges are.

01:34:11.980 --> 01:34:12.980
And they go over.

01:34:12.980 --> 01:34:15.980
And that would have been flat up to there.

01:34:15.980 --> 01:34:22.980
And that would have been levels going back 150 years.

01:34:22.980 --> 01:34:29.980
So no, we wouldn't consider...

01:34:29.980 --> 01:34:35.980
Once we get up through Liswery, we don't think of it any longer as being part of the Moors as we called it.

01:34:35.980 --> 01:34:39.980
So was Newport the place where you would go shopping or livestock market?

01:34:39.980 --> 01:34:41.980
Oh, yes, yes.

01:34:41.980 --> 01:34:45.980
The fresh fruit and veg market?

01:34:45.980 --> 01:34:51.980
Oh, definitely. On a Wednesday, the farmers would go to market.

01:34:51.980 --> 01:34:54.980
Their wives didn't drive, so the wives went.

01:34:54.980 --> 01:35:00.980
And I remember all my aunts who were farmers' wives who had all meeting Newport.

01:35:00.980 --> 01:35:06.980
Every shop, every building was a shop with something that people needed.

01:35:06.980 --> 01:35:10.980
And the market was a hive of industry.

01:35:10.980 --> 01:35:14.980
Griffin Street, where our shop was, was alive with shops.

01:35:14.980 --> 01:35:17.980
And people could park anywhere.

01:35:17.980 --> 01:35:23.980
I remember we used to park outside the town hall where the clock was because the bank was next door.

01:35:23.980 --> 01:35:26.980
I remember feeding the babies in the car.

01:35:26.980 --> 01:35:30.980
We used to take hot water flasks to feed.

01:35:30.980 --> 01:35:34.980
And you met everybody. You bumped into people.

01:35:34.980 --> 01:35:38.980
There was every type of business you could imagine.

01:35:38.980 --> 01:35:47.980
Expensive jewellery shops, beautiful cafes, all with different character of their own.

01:35:47.980 --> 01:35:54.980
And you always had a second story like the Cardoma where you could look down into the street and see what's around.

01:35:54.980 --> 01:35:59.980
Beautiful dress shops, lovely stores.

01:35:59.980 --> 01:36:08.980
I can remember one shop EG Taylor where they had a machine that took your money and it flew right across the shop on a chain.

01:36:08.980 --> 01:36:16.980
And it came out the other end and then you had to change back and unscrew these little pots and your money would be in it.

01:36:16.980 --> 01:36:24.980
So, yeah, beautiful shoe shops, wonderful tailors, bespoke tailors as well.

01:36:24.980 --> 01:36:30.980
I can remember my father having his coats made with this bespoke tailor and his shoes.

01:36:30.980 --> 01:36:34.980
He used to wear britches up to his knees.

01:36:34.980 --> 01:36:37.980
Britches, no, what do you call them?

01:36:37.980 --> 01:36:38.980
Leggings.

01:36:38.980 --> 01:36:40.980
Leggings up to the top of his britches.

01:36:40.980 --> 01:36:41.980
That wood button.

01:36:41.980 --> 01:36:42.980
Yes, that's it.

01:36:42.980 --> 01:36:45.980
He used to wear those and sports coats he'd have made.

01:36:45.980 --> 01:36:48.980
Yellow waistcoats.

01:36:48.980 --> 01:36:52.980
And my mother used to have her suits tailored.

01:36:52.980 --> 01:37:00.980
Oh yes, Newport was alive and gorgeous properties like the town hall and the library and everything.

01:37:00.980 --> 01:37:02.980
And they just knocked it all down.

01:37:02.980 --> 01:37:10.980
And the Lyceum Theatre with these wonderful structure with all these pillars, a bit like Covent Garden, the Opera House.

01:37:10.980 --> 01:37:19.980
And I can remember my mother taking me to pantomimes there and seeing ice skating on ice in those days.

01:37:19.980 --> 01:37:24.980
There were music halls, there were dance places.

01:37:24.980 --> 01:37:28.980
It was just wonderful.

01:37:28.980 --> 01:37:38.980
And we used to have a carnival and we'd be taken in and you'd sit on the windows of the bank or something and wait for the carnival to go past.

01:37:38.980 --> 01:37:40.980
It was huge.

01:37:40.980 --> 01:37:47.980
But the population of Newport wouldn't have been any more than about 25,000 in those days, maybe 30.

01:37:47.980 --> 01:37:49.980
And now we're looking at 100 and not 1000.

01:37:49.980 --> 01:37:51.980
It sounds like it was a thriving place.

01:37:51.980 --> 01:37:52.980
Oh it was.

01:37:52.980 --> 01:37:56.980
But you had lots of industry and the docks were huge then too, weren't they?

01:37:56.980 --> 01:38:03.980
Yes, there was industry down there and of course there was Lysats and all the other places, all of that.

01:38:03.980 --> 01:38:13.980
But the farmers would stand market Fridays and Saturdays and the market, at the top of the market you had this huge floor

01:38:13.980 --> 01:38:19.980
where all the farmers would have their chicken and their produce, their butter and their cream all the way round.

01:38:19.980 --> 01:38:27.980
And our shop was absolutely thriving in Griffin Street because people could pull up outside the market opposite the shop.

01:38:27.980 --> 01:38:31.980
We had mobile shops that used to go around the villages on a Tuesday.

01:38:31.980 --> 01:38:32.980
Oh really?

01:38:32.980 --> 01:38:39.980
They would deliver all the meat on a Saturday for people's roasts in all the villages.

01:38:39.980 --> 01:38:43.980
So all my aunts and uncles worked in this business.

01:38:43.980 --> 01:38:48.980
So it was one of the bigger butchers' shops in Newport.

01:38:48.980 --> 01:38:57.980
And yes, and I was told many stories by many people that during the war,

01:38:57.980 --> 01:39:04.980
my grandfather used to supply an awful lot of businesses with meat.

01:39:04.980 --> 01:39:12.980
But on a Saturday night, there were a lot of people down the pill area and the poorer areas of Newport who didn't have money

01:39:12.980 --> 01:39:16.980
and the kids would be without shoes and so forth.

01:39:16.980 --> 01:39:22.980
And my grandfather would hold an auction on a Saturday night because they had no cold stores you see.

01:39:22.980 --> 01:39:25.980
So all the meat that was killed had to be got rid of.

01:39:25.980 --> 01:39:32.980
So he'd auction off this meat and he used to make sure he'd auction it off to people for nothing.

01:39:32.980 --> 01:39:34.980
So they had meat for Sundays.

01:39:34.980 --> 01:39:35.980
Wow.

01:39:35.980 --> 01:39:43.980
If anybody came up with, looked a bit poor, he would make sure they had.

01:39:43.980 --> 01:39:51.980
And one day I was with the NFU doing a stand-up job in Newport Square

01:39:51.980 --> 01:39:59.980
trying to present to people what farmers could produce.

01:39:59.980 --> 01:40:04.980
So we wanted them to know that we were still around producing their food.

01:40:04.980 --> 01:40:08.980
And a little old lady came along and we got talking.

01:40:08.980 --> 01:40:15.980
And she said, oh, I've always bought my stuff in the market and I liked fresh food.

01:40:15.980 --> 01:40:21.980
And she said, and there was an old gentleman, Mr. Collymore, when we were children, we couldn't afford meat.

01:40:21.980 --> 01:40:28.980
And my mother used to come and take us children down there and we'd always have something for Sunday.

01:40:28.980 --> 01:40:30.980
And I thought, oh, well, that story was true.

01:40:30.980 --> 01:40:32.980
Oh, that's lovely, isn't it?

01:40:32.980 --> 01:40:33.980
It was nice to hear.

01:40:33.980 --> 01:40:36.980
Yeah, yeah, to have it confirmed by a third party as well.

01:40:36.980 --> 01:40:42.980
Yes, because a lot of people used to talk about it and I never knew for sure until this lady.

01:40:42.980 --> 01:40:48.980
I thought, what a coincidence that I should talk to her.

01:40:48.980 --> 01:40:54.980
Do you know places like Redwick and Furtherfield, Mega and Rocket?

01:40:54.980 --> 01:40:59.980
Do you consider them, they consider themselves to be the Moors?

01:40:59.980 --> 01:41:00.980
They talk about the Moors.

01:41:00.980 --> 01:41:01.980
Yeah.

01:41:01.980 --> 01:41:03.980
Do you from here consider them to be the Moors?

01:41:03.980 --> 01:41:04.980
Oh, yes, yes.

01:41:04.980 --> 01:41:12.980
And so is there any relation to them or are all the villages here quite separate?

01:41:12.980 --> 01:41:19.980
I think we've become more related of latter years since the children have been going to Mega school from this area.

01:41:19.980 --> 01:41:20.980
Oh, OK.

01:41:20.980 --> 01:41:23.980
And you get to know all the mums and whatever.

01:41:23.980 --> 01:41:33.980
We've always connected from the farming point of view because a lot of my relatives and a lot of David's relatives live in those areas, in all those villages.

01:41:33.980 --> 01:41:41.980
When I was at school and my friends lived over that area, I was often staying up there.

01:41:41.980 --> 01:41:44.980
And I remember the hunt coming into the square at Mega.

01:41:44.980 --> 01:41:49.980
And it was just a tiny little village, Mega was, when we were children.

01:41:49.980 --> 01:41:54.980
That you'd walk down to from whoever's home you were staying at.

01:41:54.980 --> 01:41:55.980
Yeah.

01:41:55.980 --> 01:42:00.980
And I suppose we've seen that grow into almost a town size.

01:42:00.980 --> 01:42:01.980
And that's strange.

01:42:01.980 --> 01:42:03.980
It's changed everything.

01:42:03.980 --> 01:42:05.980
And the road system round.

01:42:05.980 --> 01:42:14.980
When they came and put Tesco's there, that change started to change Mega and the brewery and all of that.

01:42:14.980 --> 01:42:16.980
So, yes, we still feel relatively.

01:42:16.980 --> 01:42:22.980
And of latter years we've become a ministry area, a benefits area.

01:42:22.980 --> 01:42:33.980
But through the churches, for the last 30, perhaps 35 years, I've been connected with all the churches out there through my work.

01:42:33.980 --> 01:42:34.980
Yeah.

01:42:34.980 --> 01:42:36.980
And you get to know more people.

01:42:36.980 --> 01:42:40.980
So, I have felt connected for a very long time.

01:42:40.980 --> 01:42:42.980
And I'm sure there are other people like me.

01:42:42.980 --> 01:42:52.980
Maybe not many, but some of us have been involved with church life in that particular area.

01:42:52.980 --> 01:42:55.980
Would you say it's still strong here, too, church life?

01:42:55.980 --> 01:42:57.980
No, nothing like it was.

01:42:57.980 --> 01:42:58.980
No.

01:42:58.980 --> 01:43:00.980
No, it's quite sad.

01:43:00.980 --> 01:43:04.980
Our congregation has dwindled with age.

01:43:04.980 --> 01:43:10.980
And, yes, it is a huge change.

